     The sensors were fabricated and calibrated by Rosemount, Inc. They were  
calibrated by immersion in baths of liquid nitrogen (77 K), liquid oxygen (89 
K), ice water (273 K), boiling water (373 K), and against a secondary standard
at 477 K. The sensors were enclosed in plastic bags and were fully immersed in
the calibration bath and left until resistances were stable. The resistances  
at known temperatures were then used to calculate constants in the familiar   
Callendar-Van Dusen equation (see, e.g., Riddle et al., 1973) for purposes of 
interpolation between calibration points above 273 K. (The resistance function
R(T) of platinum is the basis of the International Practical Temperature      
Scale.) Below 273 K, data were referenced to the International Practical      
Temperature Scale (68), and correction curves for deviations from that scale  
were derived (Rosemount Report 27410, 1975).                                  
